  "body": "#### System information\r\n\r\nGeth version: `geth 1.10.7`\r\nOS & Version: Linux, Ubuntu 18.04 LTS\r\n\r\n#### Expected behaviour\r\nWhen I use the command line `geth --nodiscover --identity \"my etherum\" --rpc --rpccorsdomain \"*\" --datadir ./data --port \"30303\" --rpcapi \"db,eth,net,web3\" --networkid 10 --allow-insecure-unlock console 2>>geth.log` to restart geth, the `eth.blockNumber()` should returns the block number I've digged out, and the balances of accounts should not be ZERO because I indeed `miner.start()` and `eth.sendTransaction()` first time.\r\n\r\n#### Actual behaviour\r\nWhenever I start geth the second time, there is the problem. \r\n\r\n#### Steps to reproduce the behaviour\r\n1. Init with`geth --datadir ~/privatechain/data init genesis.json`;\r\n2. Start geth with the commadn line I used above;\r\n2. Create new accounts, like A(as coinbase) and B;\r\n3. A dig out some new blocks, and send several ETH to B;\r\n4. exit, and then restart. We will find the problem: eth.blockNumber() returns 0, but eth.getBlock(1 or 2 ...) returns proper block. And balances of accounts become 0.\r\n#### Backtrace\r\n\r\n````\r\n[backtrace]\r\n````\r\n\r\nWhen submitting logs: please submit them as text and not screenshots.",
